2 Data Analysis
2.1 Background
Our experimental data collection is based on the three specic goals:
1. Calibration of the Lock In Amplier to get accurate results for phase sensitive
measurements. Further, to check if the amplication factor of the lock-in amplier
remains constant over time.
2. Finding mutual inductance between two coils using Lock In Amplier.
3. Measurement of a low resistance using Lock In Amplier which would otherwise be
dicult due to inherent thermal noise in DC measurements
The basic principle of an Lock-In Amplier can be understood from following:

3 Discussion
Through this experiment we are introduced to the science and art of precision electronic
measurements. We also got to learn that precision measurements can be tricky and per-
forming the experiment by varying the parameters is a good experimental practice. We
have carried out all our measurements two times to cross check and remove the blunders.
In this experiment our main focus was to study the working and implementation of
the Lock-In technique. We also got familiar we dierent kinds of noise and got to learn
some concepts of noise spectral density, and the trade-os between random and system-
atic errors.
Out of pure curiosity, we also tried out some Lock-In amplier/noise lter models
from Git-hub. The curves plotted in the Backgroud section are obtained using the same.
The Lock-In amplier provided is an analog one based on AD630 Balanced Modula-
tor/Demodulator chip.
